# 37_objects_set_stroke — closes the appearance branch of the
# canvas-observable scripts arc (symmetric second half).
#
# s238 m1 shipped set_fill + fill query + the curvz_utils pump pair
# (fill_attr_to_fill_style / fill_style_to_fill_attr). That opened
# the appearance branch — scripts could produce a SOLID FILLED
# shape on canvas for the first time, the arc's first colour-on-
# canvas event. s239 m1 ships the symmetric companion: set_stroke
# and the stroke read query.
#
# Mirror-shape of s238 m1, materially:
#   - Same EditAppearanceCommand (the existing s167-migrated
#     command, FIFTH "fits unmodified" case for verify-before-
#     assume in a row after s236 m1 / s237 m1 / s238 m1).
#   - Same fill_attr_to_fill_style pump (stroke.paint is a
#     FillStyle so the pump operates on it without modification —
#     no new pump this milestone, just a second caller for the
#     existing one).
#   - Same direct-override semantics (a direct stroke colour set
#     breaks the stroke_swatch_id binding and the bound_style
#     binding; the capture restores them on undo).
#   - Same universal-across-SceneNode-subtypes posture (no node-
#     type refusal — set_stroke on a Group is accepted, same as
#     set_fill).
#   - Same byte-clean round-trip on canonical input forms; same
#     normalising behaviour on named colours / rgb() / rgba() /
#     uppercase hex / short hex.
#   - Same value-unchanged no-op early-return (via the renamed
#     anon helper fill_style_equals_byte_rounded — formerly
#     fill_style_equals_for_set_fill, now neutrally named because
#     set_stroke is the second caller).
#
# Material differences from set_fill (and what this smoke probes):
#   - Visual scope-limit. Fresh-mint Paths have stroke.width == 0.0
#     (SceneNode default), so set_stroke "black" lands a black
#     paint on a zero-width stroke — the canvas-visible outline
#     doesn't appear until set_stroke_width sets a nonzero width
#     in a future milestone. The smoke is TRACE-CHANNEL-ONLY on
#     the stroke side; the `stroke` query reads back the colour,
#     and that's the full validation surface for m1. Three-channel
#     acceptance for m1 = trace pass + clean build + (deferred)
#     visual outline once width verb lands. The canon "regression
#     tests own their conditions" forbids the smoke from pre-
#     setting width via the inspector to fake the visual; that
#     preconditions-violation would defeat the smoke's purpose.
#   - Axis-independence. Phase 10 sets BOTH fill and stroke on the
#     same node and asserts they hold their distinct values. This
#     is the unique-to-s239-m1 phase — without it, the smoke is
#     near-mechanical copy of smoke 36. The axis-independence
#     probe verifies that set_fill and set_stroke don't disturb
#     each other's state (EditAppearanceCommand's symmetric
#     capture is what guarantees this — each verb writes only its
#     axis's _after value and leaves the other axis at
#     _before == _after).
#
# ── Owns-its-conditions structure (CANON) ────────────────────────────────
#
# BUILD UP / VALIDATE / TEAR DOWN. The smoke mints its own test
# layer and two test objects (a Path for the colour matrix, a
# Group for the universal-class probe), validates the new surface
# end-to-end, and tears everything back down. Net structural
# change to the doc: zero. Side effect on the undo stack:
# AddNodeCommand for the mints, EditPathCommand for the geometry,
# EditAppearanceCommand entries for the set_stroke / set_fill
# calls, DeleteObjectCommand pairs for the teardown.
#
# ── Pre-stated count ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Expected: 13 pass / 0 fail / 0 error.
#
# Breakdown:
#   Phase 1 (REGISTRY):                                       → 0 asserts.
#   Phase 2 (DISPATCH — baseline count):                      → 0 asserts.
#   Phase 3 (BUILD UP — mint test_layer, mint `p` as Path,
#            geometry, baseline stroke):
#     p type == "path"                                         → 1 assert.
#     p stroke == "currentColor" (fresh-mint default)         → 1 assert.
#   Phase 4 (SET — named colour "black", normalises to hex):
#     p stroke == "#000000"                                    → 1 assert.
#   Phase 5 (SET — lowercase hex byte-clean round-trip):
#     p stroke == "#ff0000"                                    → 1 assert.
#   Phase 6 (SET — "none", byte-clean round-trip):
#     p stroke == "none"                                       → 1 assert.
#   Phase 7 (SET — "currentColor", byte-clean round-trip):
#     p stroke == "currentColor"                               → 1 assert.
#   Phase 8 (NEGATIVE — unknown token degrades to currentColor):
#     p stroke == "currentColor"                               → 1 assert.
#   Phase 9 (UNIVERSAL — set_stroke on a Group is NOT refused):
#     g type == "group", g stroke == "#0000ff"                 → 2 asserts.
#   Phase 10 (AXIS-INDEPENDENCE — fill and stroke don't disturb
#             each other on the same node):
#     p fill == "#ff0000", p stroke == "#0000ff"               → 2 asserts.
#   Phase 11 (CROSS-CHECK — find_by_type "path" still resolves):
#     found_path type == "path"                                → 1 assert.
#   Phase 12 (TEAR DOWN — round-trip count):
#     objects count == count_before                            → 1 assert.
#
# Total: 0 + 0 + 2 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 2 + 2 + 1 + 1 = 13.
#
# ── On the `stroke` read-side query ──────────────────────────────────────
#
# Returns the SVG fill-attribute string for stroke.paint, re-
# emitted via curvz_utils' fill_style_to_fill_attr pump (same pump
# that powers the `fill` query — stroke.paint is a FillStyle, so
# the pump applies without modification). Four cases mirror the
# fill query:
#   - FillStyle::None         → "none"
#   - FillStyle::CurrentColor → "currentColor"
#   - FillStyle::Solid        → "#RRGGBB" (lowercase hex)
#   - FillStyle::*Gradient    → "#RRGGBB" of first stop (fallback)
#
# The query returns the PAINT only, not width / cap / join /
# miter / opacity. Each of those five non-paint stroke fields
# will be a separate query when its matching verb lands —
# stroke_width returning a number, stroke_cap / stroke_join
# returning enum tokens. Set-side and read-side stay symmetric:
# set_stroke writes only paint, stroke query reads only paint.
#
# ── On the visual scope-limit ────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# A fresh-mint Path has stroke.width == 0.0 (SceneNode/StrokeStyle
# struct default). set_stroke "black" lands a black paint on a
# zero-width stroke — the canvas paints nothing visible, despite
# the trace showing "stroke == #000000". This is by design for
# m1: the colour-vocabulary verb (set_stroke) and the numeric-arg
# verb (set_stroke_width, m2) have materially different vocabulary
# shapes, and bundling them risks blurring the "what does this
# verb do" contract.
#
# The canvas-observable arc's appearance branch CLOSES in two
# steps: m1 (this milestone) ships the colour axis; m2 ships
# the width axis. With both landed, a script can produce a fully-
# styled visible shape on canvas — geometry from s237 m1, fill
# from s238 m1, stroke colour from s239 m1, stroke width from
# s239+ m2. The smoke 37 trace channel validates colour wiring;
# the visual outline waits for m2.
#
# ── On the axis-independence probe (Phase 10) ────────────────────────────
#
# EditAppearanceCommand captures BOTH whole-FillStyle and whole-
# StrokeStyle on both the before and after sides. set_fill writes
# its new value into fill_after and leaves stroke_after equal to
# stroke_before (the "stroke unchanged" comment in the verb body).
# set_stroke does the symmetric: writes its new value into
# stroke_after and leaves fill_after equal to fill_before.
#
# The axis-independence test sets fill RED first, then stroke
# BLUE, then asserts BOTH values. If set_stroke accidentally wrote
# its fill_after as a default-constructed FillStyle instead of
# echoing fill_before, the rect would lose its red fill when
# stroke was set. The assert catches that regression class.
# Specifically: set_fill's set_stroke counterpart in the verb
# body uses `fill_before` for BOTH fb and fa (the symmetric mirror
# of set_fill's use of `stroke_before` for both sb and sa). This
# phase is what catches a typo on either side of that mirror.
#
# ── Canvas-observable (three-channel acceptance) ─────────────────────────
#
# Trace channel: the 13 asserts above.
# Visual channel: AFTER Phase 4's set_stroke "black", the rect's
#   stroke paint is black but the rect renders no visible outline
#   (width=0). Visual channel is deferred to the m2 set_stroke_width
#   milestone, which closes the appearance branch.
# Build channel: Scott's compile.

#[sub] === Phase 1: REGISTRY ===
#[sub] `objects` should appear in the registry list — baseline.

list

#[sub] === Phase 2: DISPATCH — baseline count ===
#[sub] Captures the pre-mint object count to compare against after
#[sub] teardown.

get objects count
set count_before to result

#[sub] === Phase 3: BUILD UP — mint test layer, Path, geometry ===
#[sub] Mint a sentinel-named test layer, activate it, mint `p` as a
#[sub] Path, set its geometry to a 100×100 rect at user-origin (the
#[sub] s237 m1 user-space convention). A freshly-minted Path has
#[sub] stroke.paint defaulting to FillStyle::CurrentColor (SceneNode
#[sub] struct default), so the baseline `stroke` query returns
#[sub] "currentColor" via the pump — same baseline as fill on a
#[sub] fresh-mint Path.

layers new
set test_layer to result
layers.test_layer rename "objects_set_stroke_smoke_s239_m1"
layers.test_layer activate

objects new "path"
set p to result
objects.p set_path_data "M 0 0 L 100 0 L 100 100 L 0 100 Z"

assert objects.p type == "path"
assert objects.p stroke == "currentColor"

#[sub] === Phase 4: SET — named colour "black" normalises to hex ===
#[sub] "black" parses through the named-colour subset to (0,0,0)
#[sub] Solid; the read-side pump emits "#000000". Round-trip is
#[sub] normalising. Visual: the rect's stroke paint is now black,
#[sub] but width=0 means no outline is rendered — visual scope-
#[sub] limit closes in m2 with set_stroke_width.

objects.p set_stroke "black"
assert objects.p stroke == "#000000"

#[sub] === Phase 5: SET — lowercase hex byte-clean round-trip ===
#[sub] Lowercase "#RRGGBB" round-trips byte-clean: parser reads
#[sub] "#ff0000" to Solid (255, 0, 0); emitter writes "#ff0000"
#[sub] back via "%02x". Same byte-clean guarantee as fill.

objects.p set_stroke "#ff0000"
assert objects.p stroke == "#ff0000"

#[sub] === Phase 6: SET — "none" byte-clean round-trip ===
#[sub] FillStyle::None on stroke.paint — the explicit "no stroke
#[sub] paint" state. Distinct from "stroke defaults to CurrentColor"
#[sub] (Phase 3's baseline). With width=0 the visual is
#[sub] indistinguishable from CurrentColor; with a nonzero width
#[sub] (future m2) the rect's outline would disappear under "none"
#[sub] but show with "currentColor".

objects.p set_stroke "none"
assert objects.p stroke == "none"

#[sub] === Phase 7: SET — "currentColor" byte-clean round-trip ===
#[sub] FillStyle::CurrentColor on stroke.paint — defers to the
#[sub] containing context's colour. Mirror of fill's Phase 7.

objects.p set_stroke "currentColor"
assert objects.p stroke == "currentColor"

#[sub] === Phase 8: NEGATIVE — unknown token degrades to currentColor ===
#[sub] The pump's safe-default for unrecognised tokens is
#[sub] CurrentColor (matches SvgParser::parse_fill). Phase 7
#[sub] already set stroke to CurrentColor, so this Phase's
#[sub] set_stroke is also a no-op early-return (parsed CurrentColor
#[sub] equals existing CurrentColor on byte-rounded comparison) —
#[sub] no new EditAppearanceCommand on the undo stack. The assert
#[sub] verifies the read-side query shows the expected state
#[sub] regardless. Same shape as smoke 36's Phase 8 silent-no-op
#[sub] double coverage.

objects.p set_stroke "definitely-not-a-color-token-67890"
assert objects.p stroke == "currentColor"

#[sub] === Phase 9: UNIVERSAL — set_stroke on a Group is NOT refused ===
#[sub] Appearance lives on every SceneNode subtype. Same posture
#[sub] as set_fill — no node-type refusal, container types accept
#[sub] the verb. The Group's stroke.paint slot now carries the
#[sub] blue Solid, and the query reads it back via the pump.

objects new "group"
set g to result
objects.g set_stroke "blue"

assert objects.g type == "group"
assert objects.g stroke == "#0000ff"

#[sub] === Phase 10: AXIS-INDEPENDENCE — fill and stroke orthogonal ===
#[sub] The unique-to-s239-m1 phase. Set fill RED on `p` (which had
#[sub] stroke = currentColor from Phase 7's set + Phase 8's no-op),
#[sub] then set stroke BLUE on `p`. Assert BOTH values hold their
#[sub] expected colours independently.
#[sub]
#[sub] Why this matters: EditAppearanceCommand's symmetric capture
#[sub] takes whole-FillStyle AND whole-StrokeStyle on both before
#[sub] and after sides. set_fill writes only fill_after and echoes
#[sub] stroke_before into stroke_after; set_stroke does the
#[sub] symmetric. If either verb accidentally wrote a default-
#[sub] constructed value on the other axis instead of echoing,
#[sub] this phase catches it.

objects.p set_fill "red"
objects.p set_stroke "blue"
assert objects.p fill == "#ff0000"
assert objects.p stroke == "#0000ff"

#[sub] === Phase 11: CROSS-CHECK — find_by_type "path" still resolves ===
#[sub] Sanity check that the appearance work didn't disturb the
#[sub] iid index or break type-keyed lookups. Same shape smoke 36
#[sub] used.

objects find_by_type "path"
set found_path to result
assert objects.found_path type == "path"

#[sub] === Phase 12: TEAR DOWN ===
#[sub] Three mints (test_layer, p, g) need three matching deletes.
#[sub] DeleteObjectCommand owns the per-object snapshots (path,
#[sub] fill, stroke, etc.); no leak. count returns to count_before
#[sub] — round-trip baseline.

objects delete p
objects delete g
layers delete test_layer

get objects count
assert objects count == count_before

#[sub] === Final list — registry sanity ===
#[sub] Same shape as smoke 36's close: `objects` still present, no
#[sub] transient proxies registered.

list

#[sub] Done. The s239 m1 surface is validated:
#[sub]   - `objects.<iid> set_stroke <token>` parses the token
#[sub]     through curvz_utils' fill_attr_to_fill_style pump (same
#[sub]     pump set_fill uses — stroke.paint is a FillStyle),
#[sub]     captures the full pre-edit appearance state, writes the
#[sub]     new FillStyle onto SceneNode::stroke.paint while
#[sub]     preserving stroke.width / cap / join / miter / opacity,
#[sub]     clears the stroke_swatch_id and bound_style bindings
#[sub]     (direct-override break — undoable via the captured
#[sub]     before-state), pushes EditAppearanceCommand for undo,
#[sub]     fires the s235 m1 canvas-refresh callback at success.
#[sub]   - Same-value set_stroke is a clean no-op (no command
#[sub]     pushed, no callback fired) — Phase 8's degraded-to-
#[sub]     currentColor case after Phase 7's already-currentColor
#[sub]     exercises this.
#[sub]   - `stroke` read query returns the canonical SVG fill-
#[sub]     attribute string for stroke.paint — "none",
#[sub]     "currentColor", or lowercase "#RRGGBB" for Solid.
#[sub]     Byte-clean round-trip on canonical input forms.
#[sub]   - Unknown tokens degrade to CurrentColor (same as set_fill).
#[sub]   - set_stroke is universal across SceneNode subtypes — not
#[sub]     refused on non-Paths (same as set_fill).
#[sub]   - Axis-independence: fill and stroke are orthogonal on the
#[sub]     same node; setting one doesn't disturb the other.
#[sub]
#[sub] Pre-stated: 13 pass / 0 fail / 0 error.
#[sub]
#[sub] What's still NOT covered by m1 (and that's by design):
#[sub]   - Canvas-visible stroke outline. width=0 default means no
#[sub]     outline renders; the visual closes in m2 with
#[sub]     set_stroke_width.
#[sub]   - stroke_width / stroke_cap / stroke_join / stroke_miter /
#[sub]     stroke_opacity verbs. Each is a separate vocabulary
#[sub]     (numeric or enum), scope-limited out of this milestone.
#[sub]   - Gradient tokens on stroke. Same scope-limit as set_fill.
#[sub]   - stroke_swatch_id binding via script. Same scope-limit
#[sub]     and same future-swatches-arc dependency as set_fill.
#[sub]   - Stroke-opacity round-trip via the rgba() form. Same
#[sub]     lossy-on-alpha caveat as fill.
#[sub]   - Undo / redo exercise. Three-channel acceptance for Scott
#[sub]     visually once m2 lands.
